Requirement 4¶

Starting with:

Use the Matplotlib object-oriented interface to display the sine, cosine, tangent, and arctangent of x, each in its own plot.

In [10]:
import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

x = np.linspace(0, 10, 100)
fig, ax = plt.subplots(4, figsize=(12, 12))

# Sine plot
ax[0].plot(x, np.sin(x))
ax[0].set_title('Sine Wave')
ax[0].set_xlabel('X')
ax[0].set_ylabel('Sin(X)')

# Cosine plot
ax[1].plot(x, np.cos(x))
ax[1].set_title('Cosine Wave')
ax[1].set_xlabel('X')
ax[1].set_ylabel('Cos(X)')

# Tangent plot
ax[2].plot(x, np.tan(x))
ax[2].set_title('Tangent Wave')
ax[2].set_xlabel('X')
ax[2].set_ylabel('Tan(X)')

# Arctangent plot
ax[3].plot(x, np.arctan(x))
ax[3].set_title('Arctangent Wave')
ax[3].set_xlabel('X')
ax[3].set_ylabel('Arctan(X)')

# Adjust spacing between subplots
plt.subplots_adjust(hspace=0.5)

plt.show()

Requirement 5¶

Save the figures in the previous requirement to files and display the images from the files.

In [14]:
import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

x = np.linspace(0, 10, 100)
fig, ax = plt.subplots(4, figsize=(12, 12))

# Sine plot
ax[0].plot(x, np.sin(x))
ax[0].set_title('Sine Wave')
ax[0].set_xlabel('X')
ax[0].set_ylabel('Sin(X)')

# Cosine plot
ax[1].plot(x, np.cos(x))
ax[1].set_title('Cosine Wave')
ax[1].set_xlabel('X')
ax[1].set_ylabel('Cos(X)')

# Tangent plot
ax[2].plot(x, np.tan(x))
ax[2].set_title('Tangent Wave')
ax[2].set_xlabel('X')
ax[2].set_ylabel('Tan(X)')

# Arctangent plot
ax[3].plot(x, np.arctan(x))
ax[3].set_title('Arctangent Wave')
ax[3].set_xlabel('X')
ax[3].set_ylabel('Arctan(X)')

# Adjust spacing between subplots
plt.subplots_adjust(hspace=0.5)

# Save figures to files
plt.savefig('sine_wave.png', bbox_inches='tight')
plt.savefig('cosine_wave.png', bbox_inches='tight')
plt.savefig('tangent_wave.png', bbox_inches='tight')
plt.savefig('arctangent_wave.png', bbox_inches='tight')

# Display images from files
sine_img = plt.imread('sine_wave.png')
cosine_img = plt.imread('cosine_wave.png')
tangent_img = plt.imread('tangent_wave.png')
arctangent_img = plt.imread('arctangent_wave.png')

fig, ax = plt.subplots(2, 2, figsize=(12, 8))
ax[0, 0].imshow(sine_img)
ax[0, 0].set_title('Sine Wave')
ax[0, 1].imshow(cosine_img)
ax[0, 1].set_title('Cosine Wave')
ax[1, 0].imshow(tangent_img)
ax[1, 0].set_title('Tangent Wave')
ax[1, 1].imshow(arctangent_img)
ax[1, 1].set_title('Arctangent Wave')

plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

Requirement 6¶

Plot the sin() and cos() functions on the same graph.

In [15]:
import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Create a NumPy array with evenly spaced values from 0 to 2*pi
x = np.linspace(0, 2*np.pi, 100)

# Calculate the sine and cosine values
y_sin = np.sin(x)
y_cos = np.cos(x)

# Create a figure and axis object
fig, ax = plt.subplots()

# Plot the sine and cosine curves
ax.plot(x, y_sin, label='sin(x)')
ax.plot(x, y_cos, label='cos(x)')

# Add labels and a legend
ax.set_xlabel('X')
ax.set_ylabel('Y')
ax.set_title('Sine and Cosine Functions')
ax.legend()

# Show the plot
plt.show()

Requirement 7¶

Starting with: Plot the hyperbolic tangent (tanh()) function using six different color formats. Modify x slightly in each plot so the lines are distinct.

In [16]:
import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Create the base x array
x = np.linspace(0, 10, 1000)

# Define the color formats
color_formats = ['r', 'g', 'b', '#ff00ff', '0.5', 'tab:orange']

# Create a figure and axis object
fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(8, 6))

# Plot the tanh function with different color formats
for i, color in enumerate(color_formats):
    x_shifted = x + i * 0.1  # Shift x slightly for each plot
    y = np.tanh(x_shifted)
    ax.plot(x_shifted, y, color=color, label=f'tanh(x), color={color}')

# Add labels, title, and legend
ax.set_xlabel('X')
ax.set_ylabel('tanh(X)')
ax.set_title('Hyperbolic Tangent Function with Different Color Formats')
ax.legend()

# Show the plot
plt.show()

Requirement 8¶

Using the same x as above, plot the cosine (cos()) using 4 different color formats and 4 different line types. Modify x slightly in each plot so the lines are distinct.

In [17]:
import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

x = np.linspace(0, 2*np.pi, 100)

# Plot cosine with different colors and line styles
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))

# Plot 1: Red dashed line
plt.plot(x, np.cos(x), color='red', linestyle='--', label='Red dashed')

# Plot 2: Blue dotted line
plt.plot(x + 0.1, np.cos(x), color='blue', linestyle=':', label='Blue dotted')

# Plot 3: Green dash-dot line
plt.plot(x + 0.2, np.cos(x), color='green', linestyle='-.', label='Green dash-dot')

# Plot 4: Purple solid line
plt.plot(x + 0.3, np.cos(x), color='purple', linestyle='-', label='Purple solid')

plt.xlabel('x')
plt.ylabel('cos(x)')
plt.title('Cosine Function with Different Colors and Line Styles')
plt.legend()
plt.grid(True)
plt.show()

Requirement 12¶

Use RandomState() and plot() to demonstrate 11 different plot marker types. Also, display the markers in a legend

In [21]:
import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Set up random number generator with RandomState
rng = np.random.RandomState(0)

# Generate some sample data
x = np.linspace(0, 10, 50)
y = np.sin(x) + rng.randn(50) * 0.2  # Adding some random noise

# Define marker types
markers = ['o', 's', '^', 'x', '+', 'D', 'v', '*', 'p', '>', '<']

# Plot the data with different marker types
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
for i, marker in enumerate(markers):
    plt.plot(x, y + i, marker=marker, label=f'Marker {i+1}')

plt.xlabel('x')
plt.ylabel('y')
plt.title('Different Marker Types')
plt.legend()

plt.grid(True)
plt.show()

Produce the following plot (notice the labels are darker transparency): Produce the following plot (notice the labels are darker transparency):

In [8]:
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import numpy as np

# Generate random data
np.random.seed(42)
x = np.random.normal(0, 1, 100)
y = np.random.normal(0, 1, 100)
c = np.random.random(100)  # Provide data for colormapping

# Create the plot
fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(8, 6))
scatter = ax.scatter(x, y, c=c, alpha=0.5, cmap='viridis')

# Add colorbar
cbar = fig.colorbar(scatter, ax=ax)
cbar.set_alpha(0.8)  # Set colorbar label transparency

# Add labels and title
ax.set_xlabel('X Values', fontweight='bold', alpha=0.8)  # Set x-label transparency
ax.set_ylabel('Y Values', fontweight='bold', alpha=0.8)  # Set y-label transparency
ax.set_title('Scatter Plot', fontweight='bold', alpha=0.8)  # Set title transparency

# Show the plot
plt.show()

Requirement 16¶

Produce the following plot (use errorbar()). This page will be helpful:

In [9]:
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import numpy as np

# Generate data
x = np.linspace(0, 10, 100)
y = np.sin(x)
y_err = 0.2 * np.ones_like(y)  # Constant error value of 0.2

# Create the plot
fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(8, 6))
ax.errorbar(x, y, yerr=y_err, fmt='ro', capsize=5, elinewidth=1, markeredgewidth=1, markersize=4)

# Add labels and title
ax.set_xlabel('X Values', fontweight='bold')
ax.set_ylabel('Y Values', fontweight='bold')
ax.set_title('Error Bar Plot', fontweight='bold')

# Show the plot
plt.show()

Requirement 17¶

Produce the following plot (purple and orange). This page will be helpful:

In [10]:
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import numpy as np

# Generate data
x = np.linspace(0, 5, 100)
y = np.linspace(0, 5, 100)
X, Y = np.meshgrid(x, y)
Z = np.exp(-((X - 2.5)**2 + (Y - 2.5)**2) / 0.5**2) + np.exp(-((X - 3)**2 + (Y - 1)**2) / 0.2**2)

# Create the plot
fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(8, 6))

# Plot filled contours (orange)
cont_filled = ax.contourf(X, Y, Z, levels=np.linspace(0, 1, 11), cmap='Oranges')

# Plot contour lines (purple)
cont_lines = ax.contour(X, Y, Z, levels=np.linspace(0, 1, 11), colors='purple', linewidths=0.5)

# Add a colorbar
cbar = fig.colorbar(cont_filled, ax=ax)

# Show the plot
plt.show()

Requirement 18¶

Produce the following plot. This page will be helpful:

In [11]:
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import numpy as np

# Generate data
x = np.random.randn(100000)
y = np.random.randn(100000)

# Create the plot
fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(8, 6))

# Compute the 2D histogram
counts, xbins, ybins = np.histogram2d(x, y, bins=50, range=[[-3, 3], [-4, 4]])

# Plot the 2D histogram
im = ax.pcolormesh(xbins, ybins, counts.T, cmap='inferno')

# Add a colorbar
cbar = fig.colorbar(im, ax=ax)

# Set axis limits
ax.set_xlim(-3, 3)
ax.set_ylim(-4, 4)

# Adjust the colorbar label
cbar.set_label('counts', fontweight='bold')

# Show the plot
plt.show()

Requirement 19¶

Produce the following plot (notice the color and legends).

In [20]:
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import numpy as np

# Generate data
x = np.linspace(0, 10, 100)
line_a = np.sin(x)
line_b = np.cos(x)
line_c = -np.sin(x)
line_d = -np.cos(x)

# Create the plot
fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(8, 6))

# Plot the lines
ax.plot(x, line_a, color='green', label='line A')
ax.plot(x, line_b, color='green', linestyle=':', label='line B')
ax.plot(x, line_c, color='green', linestyle='-.', label='line C')
ax.plot(x, line_d, color='green', linestyle='--', label='line D')

# Add legend
ax.legend()

# Set axis limits
ax.set_xlim(0, 10)
ax.set_ylim(-3, 3)

# Add labels and title
ax.set_xlabel('X Values', fontweight='bold')
ax.set_ylabel('Y Values', fontweight='bold')
ax.set_title('Line Plot', fontweight='bold')

# Show the plot
plt.show()
